  <para>
    Select all the &nodes; on the internal boundaries of the &skel;.
    These are the &nodes; that are part of &elems; that have different
    dominant <link linkend="Section-Concepts-PixelCategory">pixel
    categories</link>.  That is, the dominant pixel types within the
    &elems; have different assigned &materials; or belong to different
    <link linkend="Section-Concepts-Microstructure-Pixel_Group">pixel
    groups</link>.
  </para>
  <para>
    Note that the resulting &node; selection does not
    include &nodes; that are on the exterior of the &micro;, except
    where an interior boundary reaches the perimeter.
  </para>
  <figure id="Figure-boundary_nodes">
    <title>Selecting Internal Boundary Nodes</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata format="PNG" fileref="FIGURES/skel_selection/nodes_internal_boundary.png"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata format="EPS" fileref="FIGURES/skel_selection/nodes_internal_boundary.eps"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<para>
	  With pixels grouped according to the three colors in the
	  image, the pixels on the internal boundaries are shown by
	  the large blue dots.
	</para>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>

